00:13:32,771 --> 00:13:35,732
is he would be working
at his desk, bent over writing,

252
00:13:35,899 --> 00:13:38,026
and he would need something
across the room--

253
00:13:38,193 --> 00:13:39,402
a document or something.

254
00:13:39,569 --> 00:13:40,779
He would get up

255
00:13:40,946 --> 00:13:42,322
and never get out
of that crouched position,

256
00:13:42,489 --> 00:13:44,409
go over there and pick up
the document he'd need,

257
00:13:44,449 --> 00:13:46,201
and come back to his desk
and sit down again

258
00:13:46,368 --> 00:13:47,911
without ever having
straightened up.

259
00:13:48,078 --> 00:13:50,247
It's an example of how
he could concentrate.

260
00:13:50,413 --> 00:13:54,918
He drank bourbon,
and he got drunk easily.

261
00:13:55,085 --> 00:13:58,421
A galena neighbor, John rawlins,
was made his chief of staff

262
00:13:58,588 --> 00:14:01,508
and took it upon himself
to keep Grant sober.

263
00:14:04,052 --> 00:14:06,555
Grant never got drunk
when his wife was around.

264
00:14:06,721 --> 00:14:09,683
There was only two conditions
Grant would drink under.

265
00:14:09,850 --> 00:14:11,309
One was his wife wasn't there,

266
00:14:11,476 --> 00:14:13,562
and the other was there
wasn't anything going on.

267
00:14:13,728 --> 00:14:17,399
He went on a true bender
during the vicksburg campaign,

268
00:14:17,566 --> 00:14:19,276
but it was when
nothing was happening.

269
00:14:19,442 --> 00:14:21,236
It was if he--

270
00:14:21,403 --> 00:14:22,571
whether it was
anything sexual

271
00:14:22,737 --> 00:14:24,072
about his wife
being out of touch,

272
00:14:24,239 --> 00:14:25,699
I'm not too sure about,

273
00:14:25,866 --> 00:14:28,243
but I do know
that it was, boredom

274
00:14:28,410 --> 00:14:32,163
that would--
that would make him drink.

275
00:14:32,330 --> 00:14:34,416
Now he traveled south
to Meade's headquarters

276
00:14:34,583 --> 00:14:37,294
at Brandy station
near culpeper, Virginia--

277
00:14:37,460 --> 00:14:40,755
the largest union encampment
of the war.

278
00:14:42,674 --> 00:14:46,136
"April 19. YESTERDAY
THE 6th CORPS WAS REVIEWED

279
00:14:46,303 --> 00:14:49,431
"by lieutenant general
U.S. Grant.

280
00:14:49,598 --> 00:14:51,391
"He is a short, thickset man

281
00:14:51,558 --> 00:14:54,603
"and rode his horse
like a bag of meal.

282
00:14:54,769 --> 00:14:57,230
"I was a little disappointed
in the appearance,

283
00:14:57,397 --> 00:15:00,150
but I liked
the look of his eye."

284
00:15:00,317 --> 00:15:03,570
Elisha hunt rhodes.

285
00:15:03,737 --> 00:15:08,700
"We all felt at
last that the boss had arrived."

286
00:15:08,867 --> 00:15:10,548
While Grant
conferred with Meade,

287
00:15:10,619 --> 00:15:13,121
members of his staff
described Grant's triumphs

288
00:15:13,288 --> 00:15:14,706
in the west.

289
00:15:14,873 --> 00:15:18,585
Veterans of the army of
the potomac were not impressed.

290
00:15:18,752 --> 00:15:20,629
"That may be," one said,

291
00:15:20,795 --> 00:15:23,131
"but Grant
never met Bobby Lee."

292
00:15:35,560 --> 00:15:39,856
"Can anybody say
they know the general?

293
00:15:40,023 --> 00:15:41,483
"I doubt it.

294
00:15:41,650 --> 00:15:48,114
He looks so cold,
quiet, and grand."

295
00:15:48,281 --> 00:15:50,659
"I think that Lee
should have been hanged.

296
00:15:50,825 --> 00:15:53,411
"It was all the worse
that he was a good man

297
00:15:53,578 --> 00:15:57,165
"and a fine character
and acted conscientiously.

298
00:15:57,332 --> 00:16:00,335
"It's always the good men
who do the most harm

299
00:16:00,502 --> 00:16:02,170
in the world."

300
00:16:02,337 --> 00:16:05,006
Henry Adams.

301
00:16:05,173 --> 00:16:08,677
Lee is, one of the most
difficult people to talk about

302
00:16:08,843 --> 00:16:10,720
because
he's been immortalized,

303
00:16:10,887 --> 00:16:13,348
or as they call him now,
some people, "the marble man."

304
00:16:13,515 --> 00:16:19,354
He's been dehumanized
by the glory and the worship.

305
00:16:19,521 --> 00:16:22,857
He was a warm,
outgoing man,

306
00:16:23,024 --> 00:16:27,362
always had time for any private
soldier's complaint.

307
00:16:27,529 --> 00:16:29,614
Once a northern soldier

308
00:16:29,781 --> 00:16:31,741
being marched
to the rear as a prisoner

309
00:16:31,908 --> 00:16:34,661
complained to Lee in person
that someone had taken his hat.

310
00:16:34,828 --> 00:16:36,287
And he said, "that man got it."

311
00:16:36,454 --> 00:16:38,581
And Lee made the man
give him his hat back.

312
00:16:40,625 --> 00:16:43,586
The man Grant faced across
the rapidan river in Virginia

313
00:16:43,753 --> 00:16:45,422
came from a family
as celebrated

314
00:16:45,588 --> 00:16:47,549
as Grant's was obscure.

315
00:16:47,716 --> 00:16:51,345
Robert e. Lee
was born in 1807

316
00:16:51,511 --> 00:16:54,180
at stratford in
westmoreland county, Virginia,

317
00:16:54,347 --> 00:16:56,558
and was raised by his mother.

318
00:16:56,725 --> 00:16:58,768
She taught him to revere
general Washington,

319
00:16:58,935 --> 00:17:00,395
a neighbor remembered,

320
00:17:00,562 --> 00:17:04,482
"to practice self-denial
and self-control" in all things.

321
00:17:04,649 --> 00:17:06,526
His father,
"light horse Harry" Lee,

322
00:17:06,693 --> 00:17:08,293
had been a friend
and favorite lieutenant

323
00:17:08,403 --> 00:17:10,321
of George Washington,

324
00:17:10,488 --> 00:17:14,242
but light horse Harry also
squandered two wives' fortunes

325
00:17:14,409 --> 00:17:17,245
before deserting his family
for the west indies.

326
00:17:18,663 --> 00:17:20,040
At west point,

327
00:17:20,206 --> 00:17:23,209
Robert e. Lee did not earn
a single demerit.

328
00:17:23,376 --> 00:17:26,087
Classmates called him
"the marble model,"

329
00:17:26,254 --> 00:17:29,507
but liked him in spite
of his perfection.

330
00:17:29,674 --> 00:17:35,013
He was graduated second
in his class in 1829.

331
00:17:35,180 --> 00:17:37,057
In 1831, he married

332
00:17:37,223 --> 00:17:40,810
Martha Washington's
granddaughter, Mary custis.

333
00:17:40,977 --> 00:17:42,729
She bore him seven children

334
00:17:42,896 --> 00:17:47,817
and endured his long absences
as best she could.

335
00:17:47,984 --> 00:17:51,071
The mansion at Arlington
with its 250 slaves

336
00:17:51,237 --> 00:17:54,616
was her home
before it was his.

337
00:17:54,783 --> 00:17:58,328
Appointed to the prestigious
corps of engineers,

338
00:17:58,495 --> 00:18:00,246
he was three times
promoted for bravery

339
00:18:00,413 --> 00:18:01,956
during the Mexican war,

340
00:18:02,123 --> 00:18:06,127
where he once met
a young ulysses s. Grant.

341
00:18:06,294 --> 00:18:09,422
Superintendent of west point,
captor of John brown,

342
00:18:09,589 --> 00:18:10,757
he was at the start
of the war

343
00:18:10,924 --> 00:18:14,177
the nation's
most promising soldier.

344
00:18:14,344 --> 00:18:18,973
In 1861, Lee refused command
of the union army

345
00:18:19,140 --> 00:18:21,267
and followed his state
out of the union,

346
00:18:21,434 --> 00:18:24,395
not because he approved
of slavery or secession,

347
00:18:24,562 --> 00:18:28,942
but because he believed
his first duty was to Virginia.

348
00:18:30,902 --> 00:18:34,906
"I did only
what my duty demanded.

349
00:18:35,073 --> 00:18:36,991
"I could have taken
no other course

350
00:18:37,158 --> 00:18:40,161
without dishonor."

351
00:18:40,328 --> 00:18:45,166
"The man who stood before
us was the realized king Arthur.

352
00:18:45,333 --> 00:18:47,252
"The soul that looked
out of his eyes

353
00:18:47,418 --> 00:18:49,045
"was as hon est and fearless

354
00:18:49,212 --> 00:18:51,589
"as when it first
looked out on life.

355
00:18:51,756 --> 00:18:54,759
"One saw the character
as clear as crystal,

356
00:18:54,926 --> 00:18:56,845
"without complication,

357
00:18:57,011 --> 00:19:02,308
and the heart as tender
as that of ideal woman hood."

358
00:19:04,394 --> 00:19:08,022
A union girl watching Lee
ride past her Pennsylvania home

359
00:19:08,189 --> 00:19:11,276
said, "i wish he were ours."

360
00:19:13,319 --> 00:19:15,029
Early in the war,
he was ridiculed

361
00:19:15,196 --> 00:19:16,322
as "the king of spades"

362
00:19:16,489 --> 00:19:18,700
because of his fondness
for entrenching

363
00:19:18,867 --> 00:19:24,038
and "granny Lee" because of
his gray hair and strict ways,

364
00:19:24,205 --> 00:19:26,541
BUT AFTER HE DROVE McCLELLAN
OFF THE PENINSULA,

365
00:19:26,708 --> 00:19:28,418
stopped pope
at second manassas,

366
00:19:28,585 --> 00:19:30,503
demolished burnside
at fredericksburg,

367
00:19:30,670 --> 00:19:32,881
and destroyed hooker
at chancellorsville--

368
00:19:33,047 --> 00:19:35,216
all despite
overwhelming odds--

369
00:19:35,383 --> 00:19:38,303
he won the unshakable confidence
of Jefferson Davis

370
00:19:38,469 --> 00:19:42,098
and the unqualified love
of his officers and men.

371
00:19:42,265 --> 00:19:44,559
He is Avery great general,

372
00:19:44,726 --> 00:19:50,440
and, h-he's superb on both
the offensive and the defensive.

373
00:19:50,607 --> 00:19:52,025
He took long chances,

374
00:19:52,192 --> 00:19:54,569
but he took them
because he had to.

375
00:19:54,736 --> 00:19:56,821
If Grant had not
had superior numbers,

376
00:19:56,988 --> 00:19:59,908
he might have taken chances
as long as Lee took.

377
00:20:00,074 --> 00:20:02,076
The only way to win
was with long chances,

378
00:20:02,243 --> 00:20:04,037
and it made him brilliant.

379
00:20:05,914 --> 00:20:08,750
No one ever called him
Bobby Lee to his face.

380
00:20:08,917 --> 00:20:10,585
His men called him
"marse Robert"

381
00:20:10,752 --> 00:20:12,378
or "uncle Robert."

382
00:20:12,545 --> 00:20:13,755
He had a terrible temper,

383
00:20:13,922 --> 00:20:16,549
which he worked all his life
to control.

384
00:20:16,716 --> 00:20:21,429
When angered,
his icy stare was unforgettable.

385
00:20:21,596 --> 00:20:22,931
There was a young man
brought before him

386
00:20:23,097 --> 00:20:24,724
for some infraction
of the rules,

387
00:20:24,891 --> 00:20:27,518
and can you imagine being
brought before general Lee

388
00:20:27,685 --> 00:20:29,854
for having broken the rules?

389
00:20:30,021 --> 00:20:31,356
And the young man was trembling,

390
00:20:31,522 --> 00:20:33,608
and Lee said,
"you need not be afraid.

391
00:20:33,775 --> 00:20:35,151
You'll get justice here,"

392
00:20:35,318 --> 00:20:36,778
and the young man said,
"i know it, general.

393
00:20:36,945 --> 00:20:38,029
That's what I'm scared of."

394
00:20:38,196 --> 00:20:41,991
Ha ha ha ha!

395
00:20:42,158 --> 00:20:45,119
He referred to
the union army as "those people"

396
00:20:45,286 --> 00:20:47,163
rather than as "the enemy."

397
00:20:47,330 --> 00:20:50,250
Now "those people"
had a new commander

398
00:20:50,416 --> 00:20:52,418
whom Lee had not tested.

399
00:21:06,182 --> 00:21:09,310
When Grant began
his spring campaign of '64,

400
00:21:09,477 --> 00:21:12,230
he took what they called
"the heavies" --

401
00:21:12,397 --> 00:21:14,983
the heavy artillerymen
out of the forts in Washington

402
00:21:15,149 --> 00:21:16,526
and put them in the field.

403
00:21:16,693 --> 00:21:18,695
Many had been in the army
two or three years

404
00:21:18,861 --> 00:21:21,155
and never had heard
a shot fired in anger,

405
00:21:21,322 --> 00:21:24,659
and as these units marched
into camp,

406
00:21:24,826 --> 00:21:27,704
they were so much larger
than the combat regiments

407
00:21:27,870 --> 00:21:30,707
that, soldiers alongside
the road used to say,

408
00:21:30,873 --> 00:21:32,083
"what division is that?"

409
00:21:32,250 --> 00:21:33,626
There were so many of them,

410
00:21:33,793 --> 00:21:35,253
but they had some fierce things.

411
00:21:35,420 --> 00:21:37,171
The first time
they'd go into combat,

412
00:21:37,338 --> 00:21:41,717
they'd have a mangled corpse-
an artillery casualty--

413
00:21:41,884 --> 00:21:44,262
by the side of the road
with a blanket over him,

414
00:21:44,429 --> 00:21:47,265
and as the new green regiments
came abreast of them,

415
00:21:47,432 --> 00:21:49,350
they'd whisk
the blanket off and say,

416
00:21:49,517 --> 00:21:52,145
"this is what's waiting
for you up ahead."

417
00:21:52,312 --> 00:21:55,065
Not a--not a--
not a very pleasant story.

418
00:21:58,443 --> 00:22:01,779
"To get possession of Lee's
army was the first object.

419
00:22:01,946 --> 00:22:03,239
"With the capture of his army,

420
00:22:03,406 --> 00:22:05,533
"Richmond would
necessarily follow.

421
00:22:05,700 --> 00:22:08,369
"It was better to fight him
outside his stronghold

422
00:22:08,536 --> 00:22:09,787
than in it."

423
00:22:09,954 --> 00:22:11,581
Ulysses s. Grant.

424
00:22:23,468 --> 00:22:25,303
"This advance by general Grant

425
00:22:25,470 --> 00:22:29,223
"inaugurated the seventh act
in the on to Richmond drama

426
00:22:29,390 --> 00:22:32,101
played by the armies
of the union."

427
00:22:32,268 --> 00:22:33,978
General John b. Gordon.

428
00:22:36,356 --> 00:22:40,276
"That man Grant will
fight us every day and every hour

429
00:22:40,443 --> 00:22:42,862
till the end of the war."

430
00:22:43,029 --> 00:22:46,115
General James longstreet.

431
00:22:46,282 --> 00:22:51,037
Grant's plan called
for four simultaneous blows.

432
00:22:51,204 --> 00:22:52,997
William tecumseh sherman
had orders

433
00:22:53,164 --> 00:22:56,959
to strike out from chattanooga
for Atlanta.

434
00:22:57,126 --> 00:23:01,339
Franz sigel would advance
up the shenandoah valley.

435
00:23:01,506 --> 00:23:03,007
Benjamin Butler
was to lead an army

436
00:23:03,174 --> 00:23:06,094
up from the James river,

437
00:23:06,260 --> 00:23:09,639
and George Gordon Meade was
to lead the army of the potomac,

438
00:23:09,806 --> 00:23:11,974
110,000 strong,

439
00:23:12,141 --> 00:23:14,018
south against Lee.

440
00:23:16,354 --> 00:23:19,190
"Wherever Lee goes,
you will go also,"

441
00:23:19,357 --> 00:23:20,900
Grant told Meade,

442
00:23:21,067 --> 00:23:23,861
and Grant
would come along, too.

443
00:23:24,028 --> 00:23:26,906
Lee's strategy was unchanged--

444
00:23:27,073 --> 00:23:30,952
destroy the union resolve
to wage war.

445
00:23:31,119 --> 00:23:33,246
He would refuse to fight Grant
in the open,

446
00:23:33,413 --> 00:23:36,165
force him to attack
fortified confederate positions,

447
00:23:36,332 --> 00:23:39,877
and thereby offset
Grant's superior numbers.

448
00:23:40,044 --> 00:23:41,671
The bloody cost

449
00:23:41,838 --> 00:23:44,199
of trying to force the south
back into the union at gunpoint

450
00:23:44,298 --> 00:23:49,303
would bolster antiwar sentiment
in the north.

451
00:23:49,470 --> 00:23:52,140
"If we can break up
the enemy's arrangements early

452
00:23:52,306 --> 00:23:53,891
"and throw him back,

453
00:23:54,058 --> 00:23:56,811
"he will not be able to recover
his position or his morale

454
00:23:56,978 --> 00:23:59,647
"until the presidential
election is over,

455
00:23:59,814 --> 00:24:04,068
and then we shall have a new
president to treat with."

456
00:24:04,235 --> 00:24:06,028
General James longstreet.

457
00:24:12,618 --> 00:24:15,496
"April 1, 1864.

458
00:24:15,663 --> 00:24:18,708
"The president came down
to culpeper to review the army.

459
00:24:18,875 --> 00:24:21,836
"The president was mounted
on a fractious horse.

460
00:24:22,003 --> 00:24:25,631
"Soon after the march began,
his tall hat fell off.

461
00:24:25,798 --> 00:24:27,800
"His pantaloons
slipped up to the knees,

462
00:24:27,967 --> 00:24:29,635
"showing his white
homemade drawers,

463
00:24:29,802 --> 00:24:32,013
"which presently
slipped up also,

464
00:24:32,180 --> 00:24:35,057
"revealing a long,
hairy leg.

465
00:24:35,224 --> 00:24:36,851
"While we were inclined
to smile,

466
00:24:37,018 --> 00:24:40,897
"we were, very much chagrined
to see our poor president

467
00:24:41,063 --> 00:24:44,358
compelled to endure
such... torture."

468
00:24:44,525 --> 00:24:46,319
Washington roebling.

469
00:24:46,486 --> 00:24:51,365
"On the morning
of may 4,1864,

470
00:24:51,532 --> 00:24:54,577
"we, with the entire
grand army of the potomac,

471
00:24:54,744 --> 00:24:58,039
"were in motion
toward the rapidan.

472
00:24:58,206 --> 00:25:01,834
"The dawn was clear,
warm, and beautiful.

473
00:25:02,001 --> 00:25:05,463
"As the almost countless
encampments were broken up,

474
00:25:05,630 --> 00:25:09,008
"with bands in all directions
playing lively airs,

475
00:25:09,175 --> 00:25:10,635
"banners waving,

476
00:25:10,801 --> 00:25:14,931
"regiments, brigades,
and divisions falling into line.

477
00:25:15,097 --> 00:25:17,892
"The scene, even to eyes
long familiar

478
00:25:18,059 --> 00:25:20,269
"with military displays,

479
00:25:20,436 --> 00:25:23,981
was one of unusual grandeur."

480
00:25:24,148 --> 00:25:26,609
Chaplain A.M. Stewart.

481
00:25:28,361 --> 00:25:30,905
Lee's 60,000 men
were waiting for Grant

482
00:25:31,072 --> 00:25:33,366
in the tangled thicket
known as the wilderness,

483
00:25:33,533 --> 00:25:35,117
in which they had trapped
the same army

484
00:25:35,284 --> 00:25:38,621
<i>UNDER JOSEPH HOOKER
ONLY A YEAR BEFORE.</i>

485
00:25:38,788 --> 00:25:41,749
"Covered by a dense forest

486
00:25:41,916 --> 00:25:45,253
"almost impenetrable by troops
in line of battle,

487
00:25:45,419 --> 00:25:46,879
"the undergrowth was so heavy

488
00:25:47,046 --> 00:25:49,590
"that it was scarcely possible
to see more than 100 yards

489
00:25:49,757 --> 00:25:51,425
"in any direction.

490
00:25:51,592 --> 00:25:53,512
"The movements of the enemy
could not be observed

491
00:25:53,594 --> 00:25:57,807
until the lines
were almost in collision."

492
00:25:57,974 --> 00:25:59,600
Advance units
of the union army

493
00:25:59,767 --> 00:26:02,895
camped for the night on the old
chancellorsville battlefield,

494
00:26:03,062 --> 00:26:08,109
where winter rains had
washed open the shallow graves.

495
00:26:09,610 --> 00:26:12,280
"In glades
they meet skull after skull

496
00:26:12,446 --> 00:26:14,699
"where pine cones lay--

497
00:26:14,865 --> 00:26:17,952
"the rusted gun,
green shoes full of bones,

498
00:26:18,119 --> 00:26:21,289
"the moldering coat
and cuddled-up skeleton.

499
00:26:21,455 --> 00:26:24,166
"And scores of such.

500
00:26:24,333 --> 00:26:26,586
"Some start as in dreams,

501
00:26:26,752 --> 00:26:29,130
"and comrades lost bemoan.

502
00:26:29,297 --> 00:26:33,551
"By the edge of these wilds,
stonewall had charged,

503
00:26:33,718 --> 00:26:37,096
but the year and the man
were gone."

504
00:26:42,768 --> 00:26:45,479
"It grew dark,
and we built a fire.

505
00:26:45,646 --> 00:26:47,732
"The dead
were all around us.

506
00:26:47,898 --> 00:26:52,278
"Their eyeless skulls
seemed to stare steadily at us.

507
00:26:52,445 --> 00:26:57,158
The trees swayed and sighed
gently in the soft wind."

508
00:26:57,325 --> 00:26:59,285
Private frank wilkeson.

509
00:27:04,707 --> 00:27:07,835
The battle of
the wilderness began in chaos.

510
00:27:08,002 --> 00:27:11,839
Units got lost,
fired on their own comrades.

511
00:27:12,006 --> 00:27:14,592
Officers tried to navigate
by compass.

512
00:27:27,688 --> 00:27:28,981
But on the second day,

513
00:27:29,148 --> 00:27:31,400
union forces drove through
the confederate center.

514
00:27:31,567 --> 00:27:34,362
As a worried Lee watched,

515
00:27:34,528 --> 00:27:38,658
general John gregg's texans
hurried to plug up the hole.

516
00:27:38,824 --> 00:27:41,494
"Scarce had we moved a step

517
00:27:41,661 --> 00:27:44,038
"when general Lee,
in front of the whole command,

518
00:27:44,205 --> 00:27:47,833
"raised himself in his stirrups,
uncovered his gray hairs,

519
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:49,877
"and with an earnest voice
exclaimed,

520
00:27:50,044 --> 00:27:52,755
<i>TEXANS ALWAYS MOVE THEM."</i>

521
00:28:00,429 --> 00:28:03,641
"Never before in my
lifetime did I ever see such a scene

522
00:28:03,808 --> 00:28:07,269
"as was enacted
when Lee pronounced these words.

523
00:28:07,436 --> 00:28:08,604
"A yell rent the air

524
00:28:08,771 --> 00:28:11,399
"that must have been heard
for miles around.

525
00:28:11,565 --> 00:28:13,150
"A courier riding
by my side,

526
00:28:13,317 --> 00:28:16,237
"with tears coursing
down his cheeks, exclaimed,

527
00:28:16,404 --> 00:28:20,741
<i>I WOULD CHARGE HELL ITSELF
FOR THAT OLD MAN."</i>

528
00:28:20,908 --> 00:28:24,954
The texans held the
position until reinforcements came.

529
00:28:25,121 --> 00:28:27,373
By the end of the day,

530
00:28:27,540 --> 00:28:29,333
the confederates had smashed
Grant's right,

531
00:28:29,500 --> 00:28:32,044
seized two generals
and 600 prisoners,

532
00:28:32,211 --> 00:28:34,964
and come close to cutting
the union supply line.

533
00:28:44,515 --> 00:28:49,520
Grant received these reports
without comment.

534
00:28:49,687 --> 00:28:51,480
Right in the middle
of the battle of the wilderness,

535
00:28:51,647 --> 00:28:53,107
all staff men
who had been fighting

536
00:28:53,274 --> 00:28:54,354
in the east all this time--

537
00:28:54,442 --> 00:28:56,110
and he had just come
from the west--

538
00:28:56,277 --> 00:28:58,404
kept talking about
Bobby Lee, Bobby Lee.

539
00:28:58,571 --> 00:28:59,905
He will do this
and do that other,

540
00:29:00,072 --> 00:29:01,198
and Grant finally told them,

541
00:29:01,365 --> 00:29:02,845
"I'm tired of hearing
about Bobby Lee.

542
00:29:02,950 --> 00:29:04,452
"You'd think he was going
to do a double somersault

543
00:29:04,618 --> 00:29:05,995
"and land in our rear.

544
00:29:06,162 --> 00:29:07,705
"Quit thinking about
what he's going to do to you

545
00:29:07,872 --> 00:29:09,165
"and think about what
you're going to do to him.

546
00:29:09,331 --> 00:29:10,916
Bring some guns up here."

547
00:29:11,083 --> 00:29:12,084
Things like that.

548
00:29:12,251 --> 00:29:14,295
Grant's--he's wonderful.

549
00:29:14,462 --> 00:29:19,425
The wilderness is probably not
the bloodiest battle in the war,

550
00:29:19,592 --> 00:29:25,389
but the most terrible battle
in the war in many ways.

551
00:29:25,556 --> 00:29:27,975
Grant in two days
loses more men

552
00:29:28,142 --> 00:29:30,561
than hooker did--did
at chancellorsville.

553
00:29:30,728 --> 00:29:34,148
But in the wilderness,

554
00:29:34,315 --> 00:29:38,778
the leaves from the previous
year cover the ground,

555
00:29:38,944 --> 00:29:41,530
and using the type of weapon
they used in the civil war,

556
00:29:41,697 --> 00:29:46,035
you have lots of lint
and linen smoldering,

557
00:29:46,202 --> 00:29:48,788
falling into the leaves,

558
00:29:48,954 --> 00:29:52,541
and it will set
these leaves afire,

559
00:29:52,708 --> 00:29:58,172
and men who've been shot badly
through the bowels,

560
00:29:58,339 --> 00:30:00,591
with broken legs,

561
00:30:00,758 --> 00:30:02,009
will not be able to move

562
00:30:02,176 --> 00:30:04,595
as the fire starts burning
toward them,

563
00:30:04,762 --> 00:30:09,767
and large numbers of wounded men
will perish in the flames.

564
00:30:12,144 --> 00:30:14,688
Grant's first move
had been a disaster.

565
00:30:14,855 --> 00:30:18,025
The wilderness had cost
17,000 men.

566
00:30:18,192 --> 00:30:22,154
That night, brush fires
raged through the woods.

567
00:30:22,321 --> 00:30:25,741
200 wounded federal soldiers
burned alive

568
00:30:25,908 --> 00:30:30,955
while the entrenched armies
listened to their screams.

569
00:30:31,121 --> 00:30:35,042
"I am holding my breath in
awe at the vastness of the shadow

570
00:30:35,209 --> 00:30:38,963
"that floats like a pall
over our heads.

571
00:30:39,129 --> 00:30:43,467
"It is come that man has no
longer an individual existence,

572
00:30:43,634 --> 00:30:48,639
but is counted in thousands
and measured in miles."

573
00:30:48,806 --> 00:30:50,808
Clara barton.

574
00:30:50,975 --> 00:30:53,060
In the wilderness,

575
00:30:53,227 --> 00:30:57,481
surgeons amputated limbs without
letup for more than 100 hours

576
00:30:57,648 --> 00:31:02,111
and sent back behind the lines
2,000 wounded men each day.

577
00:31:02,278 --> 00:31:05,948
"As a wounded man
was lifted on the table,

578
00:31:06,115 --> 00:31:10,077
"often shrieking with pain
as the attendants handled him,

579
00:31:10,244 --> 00:31:12,204
"the surgeon quickly
examined the wound

580
00:31:12,371 --> 00:31:15,583
"and resolved upon
cutting off the wounded limb.

581
00:31:15,749 --> 00:31:17,668
"Some ether was administered.

582
00:31:17,835 --> 00:31:20,212
"The surgeon snatched his knife
from between his teeth,

583
00:31:20,379 --> 00:31:22,172
"wiped it rapidly
once or twice

584
00:31:22,339 --> 00:31:24,550
"across his
bloodstain ed apron,

585
00:31:24,717 --> 00:31:26,176
"and the cutting began.

586
00:31:26,343 --> 00:31:29,763
"The operation accomplished,

587
00:31:29,930 --> 00:31:32,433
"the surgeon would look around
with a deep sigh

588
00:31:32,600 --> 00:31:34,226
"and then...

589
00:31:34,393 --> 00:31:35,603
<i>NEXT."</i>

590
00:31:35,769 --> 00:31:37,980
Carl schurz.

591
00:31:39,857 --> 00:31:43,694
"The wilderness
was a useless battle

592
00:31:43,861 --> 00:31:49,158
fought with great loss
and no result."

593
00:31:49,325 --> 00:31:50,993
Washington roebling.

594
00:31:53,454 --> 00:31:55,372
Grant, in the wilderness--

595
00:31:55,539 --> 00:31:57,180
after that first night
in the wilderness--

596
00:31:57,333 --> 00:32:01,003
went to his tent,
broke down, and cried very hard.

597
00:32:01,170 --> 00:32:03,339
Some
of the staff members said

598
00:32:03,505 --> 00:32:05,799
they'd never seen a man
so unstrung,

599
00:32:05,966 --> 00:32:07,968
but he didn't cry
until the battle was over,

600
00:32:08,135 --> 00:32:11,013
and he wasn't crying
when it began again next day.

601
00:32:13,098 --> 00:32:14,258
What was
different about Grant

602
00:32:14,350 --> 00:32:16,685
became clear the next morning

603
00:32:16,852 --> 00:32:19,188
when he gave the order
to march.

604
00:32:19,355 --> 00:32:21,315
For the first time
after a defeat,

605
00:32:21,482 --> 00:32:24,777
the army of the potomac
was moving forward.

606
00:32:24,944 --> 00:32:27,655
"May 7.

607
00:32:27,821 --> 00:32:30,658
"If we were under
any other general except Grant,

608
00:32:30,824 --> 00:32:32,576
"i should expect a retreat,

609
00:32:32,743 --> 00:32:35,704
but Grant is not
that kind of soldier."

610
00:32:35,871 --> 00:32:37,957
Elisha hunt rhodes.

611
00:32:41,418 --> 00:32:44,129
"Our spirits rose,"
one union man remembered.

612
00:32:44,296 --> 00:32:47,633
"We marched free.
The men began to sing."

613
00:32:47,800 --> 00:32:52,388
"Ulysses," another soldier said,
"don't scare worth a damn."

614
00:33:05,275 --> 00:33:08,404
"General Grant
is not going to retreat.

615
00:33:08,570 --> 00:33:11,448
"He will move his army
to spotsylvania.

616
00:33:11,615 --> 00:33:13,242
"I'm so sure
of his next move

617
00:33:13,409 --> 00:33:17,329
that I have already made
arrangements."

618
00:33:17,496 --> 00:33:18,956
He knew what Grant
was going to do

619
00:33:19,123 --> 00:33:20,958
because he could
make himself Grant

620
00:33:21,125 --> 00:33:22,251
for long enough
to figure out

621
00:33:22,418 --> 00:33:25,421
what Grant would do
in a situation.

622
00:33:25,587 --> 00:33:29,341
When, they fired, let's see,
five or six generals

623
00:33:29,508 --> 00:33:31,468
before they got to Grant,

624
00:33:31,635 --> 00:33:33,470
AND BY THE TIME
THEY LET McCLELLAN GO,

625
00:33:33,637 --> 00:33:36,807
Lee said, "I'm afraid they're
gonna keep making these changes

626
00:33:36,974 --> 00:33:41,812
until they get someone
i don't understand."

627
00:33:41,979 --> 00:33:44,314
They never got anyone
he didn't understand,

628
00:33:44,481 --> 00:33:46,316
but, they finally got Grant,

629
00:33:46,483 --> 00:33:48,402
who knew how to whip him
and did.

630
00:33:52,573 --> 00:33:53,949
In the first years
of the war,

631
00:33:54,116 --> 00:33:56,410
battle was bloody
but sporadic.

632
00:33:56,577 --> 00:34:00,164
From now on, it would be waged
without a break.

633
00:34:00,330 --> 00:34:01,832
From the wilderness
to cold harbor,

634
00:34:01,999 --> 00:34:05,502
it would not stop
for 30 days.

635
00:34:05,669 --> 00:34:07,421
It was, one soldier wrote,

636
00:34:07,588 --> 00:34:08,756
"living night and day

637
00:34:08,922 --> 00:34:11,675
within the valley
of the shadow of death."

638
00:34:13,093 --> 00:34:16,597
Our father,
who art in heaven...

639
00:34:16,764 --> 00:34:18,474
"May 8.

640
00:34:18,640 --> 00:34:21,268
"The dreadful work
is beginning again.

641
00:34:21,435 --> 00:34:23,520
"John l. Miller,
my cousin,

642
00:34:23,687 --> 00:34:26,440
"killed at the head
of his regiment.

643
00:34:26,607 --> 00:34:29,193
"The blows now fall so fast
on our heads,

644
00:34:29,359 --> 00:34:31,820
it is bewildering."

645
00:34:31,987 --> 00:34:33,947
Mary chesnut.

646
00:34:34,114 --> 00:34:35,449
But deliver us from evil.

647
00:34:44,291 --> 00:34:45,876
At spotsylvania,

648
00:34:46,043 --> 00:34:50,547
the two armies mauled each other
for days without gaining ground.

649
00:34:52,007 --> 00:34:54,259
It was the most
relentless exchange of fire

650
00:34:54,426 --> 00:34:57,096
in the history of warfare
up to that time.

651
00:35:00,974 --> 00:35:02,851
Some men were hit
by so many bullets

652
00:35:03,018 --> 00:35:06,271
that their bodies
fell apart.

653
00:35:06,438 --> 00:35:08,899
A union veteran remembered it

654
00:35:09,066 --> 00:35:12,444
simply as "the most terrible day
i have ever lived."

655
00:35:17,407 --> 00:35:20,536
"The enemy's dead
were piled upon each other

656
00:35:20,702 --> 00:35:22,621
"in front
of the captured breastworks,

657
00:35:22,788 --> 00:35:25,916
"in some places
four layers deep.

658
00:35:26,083 --> 00:35:31,088
"Below the mass
of fast-decaying corpses,

659
00:35:31,255 --> 00:35:33,632
"the convulsive twitching
of limbs showed

660
00:35:33,799 --> 00:35:37,136
"that there were wounded men
still alive.

661
00:35:37,302 --> 00:35:41,473
The place was well named
the bloody angle."

662
00:35:48,105 --> 00:35:51,608
The two armies lost
another 20,000 men.

663
00:35:59,950 --> 00:36:03,579
"MAY 12th,
YELLOW TAVERN, Virginia.

664
00:36:03,745 --> 00:36:07,332
General Jeb Stuart killed."

665
00:36:12,754 --> 00:36:14,381
When Lee got the news,
he said,

666
00:36:14,548 --> 00:36:17,759
"i can scarcely think of him
without weeping."

667
00:36:29,229 --> 00:36:31,565
Again and again,
Lee anticipated Grant,

668
00:36:31,732 --> 00:36:34,735
and again and again, the union
commander skirted south and east

669
00:36:34,902 --> 00:36:36,278
in a semicircle,

670
00:36:36,445 --> 00:36:39,489
the two armies locked in
a brutal, clumsy stranglehold

671
00:36:39,656 --> 00:36:43,785
as the battle lines lurched
toward Richmond.

672
00:36:43,952 --> 00:36:46,872
"We must destroy
this army of Grant's

673
00:36:47,039 --> 00:36:49,333
"before he gets
to the James.

674
00:36:49,499 --> 00:36:52,753
"If he gets there,
it will become a siege,

675
00:36:52,920 --> 00:36:56,173
and then it will be
a mere question of time."

676
00:36:56,340 --> 00:36:58,967
"MAY 11th.

677
00:36:59,134 --> 00:37:02,930
"We have now ended the sixth day
of very heavy fighting,

678
00:37:03,096 --> 00:37:06,808
"and the result up to this time
is much in our favor.

679
00:37:06,975 --> 00:37:09,603
"I propose to fight it out
on this line,

680
00:37:09,770 --> 00:37:12,481
if it takes all summer."

681
00:37:12,648 --> 00:37:16,151
Grant continued
his stubborn flanking maneuvers

682
00:37:16,318 --> 00:37:18,153
in an attempt
to get around Lee's right

683
00:37:18,320 --> 00:37:20,322
and move on Richmond.

684
00:37:26,078 --> 00:37:28,705
He did it with
superior numbers and doggedness,

685
00:37:28,872 --> 00:37:30,916
kept going,
move by the left flank,

686
00:37:31,083 --> 00:37:33,794
move by the left flank,
move by the left flank,

687
00:37:33,961 --> 00:37:35,362
and Lee's backing up
the whole time,

688
00:37:35,420 --> 00:37:37,673
losing men
that he couldn't replace.

689
00:37:37,839 --> 00:37:40,550
"May 15, 1864.

690
00:37:40,717 --> 00:37:43,053
"Dear Emily,
the papers must have told you

691
00:37:43,220 --> 00:37:45,055
"that we have been
fighting a little.

692
00:37:45,222 --> 00:37:49,059
"Our corps has only 12,000 left
out of 27,000.

693
00:37:49,226 --> 00:37:53,772
"Uncle Robert e. Lee
isn't licked yet by a long shot,

694
00:37:53,939 --> 00:37:57,734
"and if we are not mighty
careful, he'll beat us.

695
00:37:57,901 --> 00:38:02,447
"I think we have done very well
to avoid that fate so far.

696
00:38:02,614 --> 00:38:04,700
"Tomorrow we have
another battle.

697
00:38:04,866 --> 00:38:08,996
I don't think
it will amount to much."

698
00:38:09,162 --> 00:38:11,206
Washington roebling.

699
00:38:11,373 --> 00:38:16,586
Grant and Lee now raced
for a crossroads called cold harbor

700
00:38:16,753 --> 00:38:19,715
near the chickahominy river.

701
00:38:19,881 --> 00:38:22,676
Again, Lee got there first
and ordered his men to dig in

702
00:38:22,843 --> 00:38:26,430
and prepare for the all-out
assault he knew would follow.

703
00:38:29,850 --> 00:38:32,352
AS THEY SETTLED DOWN
FOR THE NIGHT ON June 2nd,

704
00:38:32,519 --> 00:38:36,481
veterans on the union side
sensed what was coming.

705
00:38:36,648 --> 00:38:39,901
"The men were calmly writing
their names and home addresses

706
00:38:40,068 --> 00:38:41,570
"on slips of paper

707
00:38:41,737 --> 00:38:44,239
"and pinning them
to the backs of their coats

708
00:38:44,406 --> 00:38:46,992
"so that their bodies
might be recognized

709
00:38:47,159 --> 00:38:51,330
and their fate made known
to their families at home."

710
00:38:51,496 --> 00:38:53,623
General Horace Porter.

711
00:38:58,837 --> 00:39:02,382
When the bugles blew
for the attack at 4:30 A.M.,

712
00:39:02,549 --> 00:39:06,845
60,000 union men started
toward the unseen enemy.

713
00:39:07,012 --> 00:39:09,264
The battle of cold harbor
had begun.

714
00:39:11,266 --> 00:39:13,769
"I had seen the dreadful
carnage in front of marye's hill

715
00:39:13,935 --> 00:39:15,270
"at fredericksburg,

716
00:39:15,437 --> 00:39:20,192
"but I had seen nothing
to exceed this.

717
00:39:20,359 --> 00:39:22,819
It was not war.
It was murder."

718
00:39:32,371 --> 00:39:34,915
Those were men who
knew how to take a position

719
00:39:35,082 --> 00:39:37,000
where you could do
the most killing from.

720
00:39:37,167 --> 00:39:38,293
When that whole army
was lined up,

721
00:39:38,460 --> 00:39:39,628
they're waiting and hoping

722
00:39:39,795 --> 00:39:41,463
and praying something
would come at them,

723
00:39:41,630 --> 00:39:45,342
and Grant threw three corps
at them,

724
00:39:45,509 --> 00:39:50,305
and in approximately 7 minutes,
they shot about 7,000 men down.

725
00:39:50,472 --> 00:39:52,641
It was a bloody mess.

726
00:39:52,808 --> 00:39:58,313
It's the only thing Grant ever
admitted that he'd done wrong.

727
00:39:58,480 --> 00:40:00,607
"I've always regretted

728
00:40:00,774 --> 00:40:05,112
"that the last assault
at cold harbor was ever made.

729
00:40:05,278 --> 00:40:06,947
"No advantage whatever
was gained

730
00:40:07,114 --> 00:40:10,367
to compensate for
the heavy loss we sustained."

731
00:40:15,831 --> 00:40:17,749
When another assault
was suggested,

732
00:40:17,916 --> 00:40:20,752
union officers
rejected the idea outright.

733
00:40:20,919 --> 00:40:24,297
"I will not take my regiment
in another such charge,"

734
00:40:24,464 --> 00:40:26,174
said a New Hampshire captain,

735
00:40:26,341 --> 00:40:28,927
"if Jesus Christ himself
should order it."

736
00:40:32,681 --> 00:40:34,516
After the battle,

737
00:40:34,683 --> 00:40:37,144
the diary of a young
Massachusetts volunteer

738
00:40:37,310 --> 00:40:40,480
was found
spattered with blood.

739
00:40:40,647 --> 00:40:42,524
Its last entry read,

740
00:40:42,691 --> 00:40:47,821
"June 3, 1864,
cold harbor, Virginia.

741
00:40:47,988 --> 00:40:49,698
I was killed."

742
00:40:59,207 --> 00:41:01,376
"Our matters here
are at a deadlock.

743
00:41:01,543 --> 00:41:03,462
"Unless the rebs
